                  <origination>
                     <persname> Davis, W. W. H. (William Watts Hart), 1820-1910</persname>
                  </origination>
                  <unittitle>Proceedings of Inter-County Historical Meeting at Hatboro, Montgomery County, Pa. July 17, 1894, 
<unitdate>1894-1902</unitdate>
                     <unitdate>1894</unitdate>
                  </unittitle>
                  <unittitle>Proceedings of Inter-County Historical Meeting at Hatboro, Montgomery County, Pa. July 17, 1894</unittitle>
                  <physdesc>
                     <extent>1 volume</extent>
                  </physdesc>
                  <langmaterial>The material is in <language>English</language>
                  </langmaterial>
                  <abstract> This 108-page scrapbook contains newspaper clippings, letters, and ephemera related to the "Inter-County Historical Meeting" of representatives from Bucks, Montgomery, and Chester counties in Pennsylvania.  At the July 17, 1894, meeting, held in Hatboro, Pennsylvania, seven speakers addressed topics related to local history, the American Revolution, and the use and study of history.  William Watts Hart Davis of Doylestown, Pennsylvania, compiled the scrapbook in the fall of 1894.</abstract>
                  <repository>
                     <corpname>
                        <subarea>William L. Clements Library</subarea>, University of Michigan</corpname>
                     <extptr/>
                  </repository>
               </did>
            </objectXMLWrap>

                  <titleInfo>
                     <title>Walter F. Price papers, 1878-1945.</title>
                  </titleInfo>
                  <abstract>Price's papers include 3 albums containing materials relating to Haverford College's Class of 1881 over time, such as class reports, photos of classmates and faculty, letters, programs, and notes. Also letters of Walter Price, including some to Mary Vaux Walcott relating to the building of the Washington, D.C. (Quaker) Meetinghouse and other correspondence relating to architectural work at Chester County Historical Society. His correspondents include Isabel Darlington, Helen Hole, Rayner Kelsey, Walter Penn Shipley, Albanus Smith, and Wilbur K. Thomas. </abstract>
                  <name>
                     <namePart>Haverford College Library</namePart>
                     <role>
                        <roleTerm valueURI="http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/rps">Repository</roleTerm>
                     </role>
                  </name>
               </mods>
            </objectXMLWrap>
